[start section id="20112"]

#1 Colon cancer
Two synchronous tumors have been surgically removed on January 26 by Dr. Wing.  The more distal is a stage III tumor while the more proximal is a stage II tumor.  All macroscopic disease was resected.  Mr. Vestal is currently without evidence of disease.  This is supported by a CT-scan performed earlier today of the abdomen that shows no evidence of tumor.  A CEA is 2.3.
I have discussed with Mr. Vestal and his wife the potential benefits and the risks of adjuvant chemotherapy.  I explained to him that the purpose of chemotherapy is to decrease the chance of recurrence.  Since Mr. Vestal is a very fit looking 83-year-old gentleman, I recommended that he start chemotherapy with FOLFOX.  I told him that often in patients his age an alternative approach is to give capecitabine only and that should he not tolerate the full FOLFOX regimen he could always change to 5-FU or capecitabine only.  We discussed the potential risks of the chemotherapy including fatigue, nausea, vomiting, immune suppression, diarrhea, mucositis, peripheral neuropathy, and cold intolerance.  Mr. Vestal stated that he understood this, and he is still eager to go ahead with the chemotherapy.  He, however, would like to have this done closer to his home in Queen.  I stated that  adjuvant chemotherapy should be started four to six-weeks after the surgical procedure.  I emphasized the need for follow-up after completion of the chemotherapy.  This should especially consist of physical examination and a repeat colonoscopy after one-year.  This should be done especially in the light of the multiple polyps found during Mr. Vestal's medical workup.
#2 Area of patchy fibrosis in the lung
This was seen on a chest x-ray.  Followup is recommended.
#3 Small gastrointestinal stromal tumor
I explained to Mr. Vestal that this was resected in its entirety and that no further follow-up is required.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

