[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Vestal's oncological history is as follows:
1.  January 20, 2010, presented to West District Center for work-up of dyspnea and iron-deficiency anemia.
2.  Colonoscopy on January 22, 2010, noted a mass in the transverse colon mass.  Pathology showed grade 3  adenocarcinoma.
3.  January 26, 2010, laparoscopic right hemicolectomy by Dr. Wing.  According to the operative report, the liver was palpated and there was felt to be no tumor.  The pathology report describes two invasive grade 3 of 4 adenocarcinomas.  Tumor #1 was located in the ascending colon, 5.8 x 4.3 x 1.6-cm; 5.5 cm from the ileocecal valve invading into the pericolic fat.  For this area, 27 lymph nodes were negative for metastatic disease.  Tumor #2 formed a 6.2- x 4.5- x 2.2-cm mass also invading into the pericolic fat.  Two out of twelve regional lymph nodes in this area were positive for metastatic disease.  Additionally, there were two hyperplastic polyps and a sessile serrated adenoma.  Of note, there was also a 0.3-cm gastrointestinal stromal tumor without mitotic activity.  The colon cancer was staged T3, N1, MX.
Mr. Vestal comes to Eastern Montana Hospital for a postoperative follow-up.  He states that his postoperative course has been benign and that he is now feeling much better than before the surgery.  His appetite is good.  He has gained some weight and is back at work.

[end section id="20103"]

